text: Um, I was born in London. I've been in West London for all of my life. I'm 27 now. I was born in hillingdon Hospital in hounslow, which is in West London. And it is on one end of the piccadilly Line, near to heathrow Airport. Some of the things I like about London are, ah, that it's very easy to get around. You, um, can meet lots of different people, people from all around the world and try a lot of different things. um, particularly food, music, um, traveling is very easy from here. um, what are some of the things I don't like about London? It's very crowded. I don't do well in crowds. It can be really gloomy, especially in the winter, which seems to last for about nine months of the year. It rains a lot. um, also I don't like that it's quite gray in terms of even the buildings and the pavements and everything is gray, except in the summer, it's fine. um, the one thing that is good though, is that you can easily get to green spaces. Apparently there are so many trees in London that it would actually officially be counted as a forest. But obviously they're not all in the same place, so it doesn't always feel like that. Do I have a favorite restaurant? M I'm not sure, actually. Have I been to any of the parks in London? And do I have a favorite park? Yes, I do. It's actually not one of the big ones. My favorite park is Austerly Park, which again is in West London where I live. um, you can get to that on the piccadilly Line as well, if you stop at Austerally Station. But it's one of their National Trust properties and it's a bit out of the way, so it doesn't get a lot of people going there. But it's got a big house, um, really big grounds. It used to belong to a family who I think owned most of that area. But they've, um, just turned the park bit of it into National Trust property. It's got a lake, um, and a river. And you can go canoeing on the river. And they have like, swans and ducks. They also have rabbits. And if you go during about the end of March, beginning of April, you can usually see baby ducks and baby rabbits. um, so it's really nice. They also have cows, horses, chickens, because they have a small working farm on the park. So it's quite fun. If someone was new to the city, I would say probably go and see the parks because they're a good escape from the general hustle and bustle. And, um, sometimes you need a break from that. I'd say do all the touristy things because some of them are quite fun. And I think especially if you live here and you've been here a long time, you do miss out on doing those. We also have lots of nice museums. um, and you can usually spend an entire day walking around one museum. One particular thing that I like doing is every year they have the National Photographer, the Nature Photographer of the Year, and they present all the pictures in the Natural History Museum. And that's always good to go and see. I haven't really been to any of the tourist attractions like the London Eye. We went on school trips, so I've been to like madame to swords and the London dungeons and stuff like that. um, generally I'd say they are probably overrated. I like more than nature stuff and parks and things like that and also going around museums at my own pace. um, other things to do in London would include I think one thing that I'm interested in doing is just going to random stations because sometimes when you're on a line so, for example, I take the big daily line every single day to work.
